<category>
    <pattern>WHAT IS A SQUAT RACK</pattern>
    <template>A squat rack is a gym station designed to hold a barbell safely for exercises such as squats, overhead press, and sometimes bench press. It includes adjustable hooks and safety bars.</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>WHAT IS SQUAT RACK</pattern>
    <template>A squat rack is a gym station designed to hold a barbell safely for exercises such as squats, overhead press, and sometimes bench press. It includes adjustable hooks and safety bars.</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>WHAT IS A TREADMILL</pattern>
    <template>A treadmill is a cardio machine that allows you to walk, jog, or run indoors on a moving belt.</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>WHAT IS TREADMILL</pattern>
    <template>A treadmill is a cardio machine that allows you to walk, jog, or run indoors on a moving belt.</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>WHAT IS A ROWING MACHINE</pattern>
    <template>A rowing machine is a cardio machine that simulates the rowing motion. It trains both the upper and lower body while also improving cardiovascular fitness.</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>WHAT IS ROWING MACHINE</pattern>
    <template>A rowing machine is a cardio machine that simulates the rowing motion. It trains both the upper and lower body while also improving cardiovascular fitness.</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>WHAT IS A PULL UP BAR</pattern>
    <template>A pull-up bar is a horizontal bar used for bodyweight pulling exercises such as pull-ups, chin-ups, and hanging leg raises.</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>WHAT IS PULL UP BAR</pattern>
    <template>A pull-up bar is a horizontal bar used for bodyweight pulling exercises such as pull-ups, chin-ups, and hanging leg raises.</template>
</category>

<!-- ============================================================ -->
<!--  GYM EQUIPMENT USAGE                                         -->
<!-- ============================================================ -->

<category>
    <pattern>WHAT IS A BARBELL USED FOR</pattern>
    <template>A barbell is mainly used for compound strength exercises such as squats, deadlifts, bench press, overhead press, and rows. It allows heavier loading and is essential for progressive overload.</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>WHAT IS A DUMBBELL USED FOR</pattern>
    <template>Dumbbells are used for many exercises including dumbbell press, curls, rows, shoulder raises, lunges, and Romanian deadlifts. They are especially useful for unilateral training.</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>WHAT IS A TREADMILL USED FOR</pattern>
    <template>A treadmill is used for walking, jogging, running, warming up, and improving cardiovascular fitness. It is also useful for calorie burning and weight management.</template>
</category>

<!-- ============================================================ -->
<!--  WARM-UP AND COOLDOWN                                        -->
<!-- ============================================================ -->

<category>
    <pattern>HOW DO I WARM UP BEFORE LIFTING</pattern>
    <template>A good warm-up before lifting includes 5 to 10 minutes of light cardio followed by dynamic stretches and a few lighter warm-up sets of your first exercise. This helps prepare your joints, muscles, and nervous system for training.</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>WHAT SHOULD I DO AFTER A WORKOUT</pattern>
    <template>After a workout, do a short cooldown, rehydrate, stretch the muscles you trained, and eat a meal containing protein and carbohydrates. Good sleep is also very important for recovery.</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>HOW DO I COOL DOWN AFTER TRAINING</pattern>
    <template>A proper cooldown includes 5 minutes of light movement followed by static stretching for the muscles you trained. This helps gradually lower your heart rate and improve flexibility.</template>
</category>

<!-- ============================================================ -->
<!--  TRAINING FREQUENCY                                          -->
<!-- ============================================================ -->

<category>
    <pattern>HOW OFTEN SHOULD I TRAIN LEGS</pattern>
    <template>For most people, training legs 2 times per week is a good balance between progress and recovery. Beginners on full-body programmes may train legs 3 times per week with lighter overall volume.</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>HOW OFTEN SHOULD I GO TO THE GYM</pattern>
    <template>For general fitness and muscle building, 3 to 5 gym sessions per week is a strong target. Beginners usually do well with 3 sessions per week.</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>HOW MANY DAYS A WEEK SHOULD I TRAIN</pattern>
    <template>Beginners usually train 3 days per week, intermediate lifters often train 4 days per week, and more advanced lifters may train 5 or 6 days depending on programme design and recovery.</template>
</category>

<!-- ============================================================ -->
<!--  BEGINNER GUIDANCE                                           -->
<!-- ============================================================ -->

<category>
    <pattern>I AM A BEGINNER AT THE GYM</pattern>
    <template>As a beginner, focus on learning the fundamental compound exercises, using light weights, and building consistency. Training 3 times per week with a simple full-body programme is a strong starting point.</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>WHERE DO I START AT THE GYM</pattern>
    <template>Start by learning the basic compound exercises such as squat, deadlift, bench press, row, and overhead press. Use light weights, focus on technique, and follow a simple structured beginner programme.</template>
</category>

<!-- ============================================================ -->
<!--  RECOVERY AND MUSCLE SORENESS                                -->
<!-- ============================================================ -->

<category>
    <pattern>WHY ARE MY MUSCLES SORE AFTER THE GYM</pattern>
    <template>Muscle soreness after training is often DOMS, which stands for Delayed Onset Muscle Soreness. It happens after challenging exercise and usually fades within a few days.</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>HOW LONG SHOULD I REST BETWEEN WORKOUTS</pattern>
    <template>You should usually allow at least 48 hours before training the same muscle group again. Recovery depends on training intensity, volume, sleep, and nutrition.</template>
</category>

<!-- ============================================================ -->
<!--  GENERAL TRAINING DEFINITIONS                                -->
<!-- ============================================================ -->

<category>
    <pattern>WHAT IS A COMPOUND EXERCISE</pattern>
    <template>A compound exercise is a movement that uses multiple joints and muscle groups at the same time. Examples include squats, deadlifts, bench press, rows, and pull-ups.</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>WHAT IS PROGRESSIVE OVERLOAD</pattern>
    <template>Progressive overload means gradually increasing the training challenge over time by adding weight, reps, sets, or improving technique so that your body keeps adapting.</template>
</category>

<!-- ============================================================ -->
<!--  GOODBYE                                                     -->
<!-- ============================================================ -->

<category>
    <pattern>BYE</pattern>
    <template>Goodbye! Keep training hard and stay consistent. Remember — progress comes from showing up. Good luck!</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>GOODBYE</pattern>
    <template>See you next time! Stay consistent, train smart, and recover well. Goodbye!</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>THANK YOU</pattern>
    <template>You're welcome! Good luck with your training. Feel free to ask me anything else about gym exercises, technique, or recovery.</template>
</category>

<category>
    <pattern>THANKS</pattern>
    <template>No problem! Keep training consistently and the results will come. Ask me anything else anytime.</template>
</category>

